{
  "texts": [
    "We intuitively appreciate this, which is what accounts for the sense that deviant causal chains do not support rational agency.",
    "But we cannot make use of this insight if we are, as Davidson is, committed to understanding the relation between psychological cause and environmental effect without reference to a brainexternal teleological structure.",
    "In this way, Anscombe drops a constraint that Davidson insists on.",
    "For her, what matters is that a material process, intelligible as targeted towards an intentional end, exhibits the structure that practically rational beings like us are attuned to in our practices of asking for and answering 'why?'",
    "questions of the type she puts at the centre of her account."
  ]
}